ot only how gender, history, and culture shaped the project's trajectory, but also how, even in its stalled state, the deal upended social life on the land by setting in motion incomplete processes of development and dispossession. With rich ethnographic detail and visual storytelling, Sweet Deal, Bitter Landscape traces the lived experiences of diverse rural women and men as they struggled for survival under a seemingly endless condition of liminality. In so doing, she raises critical questions about the directions and stakes of postcolonial development and nation-building in Tanzania, and the shifting meanings of identity and belonging for those on the margins of capitalist agrarian transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLand tenurexSocial aspectszTanzania. 0aRural developmentxPolitical aspectszTanzania. 0aRural developmentzTanzania. 0aWomenzTanzaniaxSocial conditions. 4aAFRICAN HIST & DIASPORA. 4aGENDER STUDIES. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aagrarian politics, global land grab, coastal Tanzania, international deals, liminality, feminist perspective.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501772023zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501772023zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501772023/original  a978-3-11-075184-0 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA